@skottmckay You were right, it had to do with including dnnl.dll in the output directory.

Now I am having an issue with TensorRT.  I built with TensorRT 7 Cuda 10.2.

When I run with CUDA, everything is fine:
`
            // Create session options and set the graph optimization level for the session
            SessionOptions options = new SessionOptions();
            int gpuDeviceId = 0; // The GPU device ID to execute on
            options.AppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(gpuDeviceId);
            //options.AppendExecutionProvider_Tensorrt(gpuDeviceId);
            options.GraphOptimizationLevel = GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_ALL;

            ...

            using (var session = new InferenceSession(modelPath, options))
            {
                 ....
            }
`

However, I get an error when trying to run using TensorRT:
`
            // Create session options and set the graph optimization level for the session
            SessionOptions options = new SessionOptions();
            int gpuDeviceId = 0; // The GPU device ID to execute on
            //options.AppendExecutionProvider_CUDA(gpuDeviceId);
            options.AppendExecutionProvider_Tensorrt(gpuDeviceId);
            options.GraphOptimizationLevel = GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_ALL;

            ...

            using (var session = new InferenceSession(modelPath, options))
            {
                 ....
            }
`

I've included the following files in the output directory:
- cudart64_102.dll
- cublasLt64_10.dll
- cudnn64_7.dll
- cublas64_10.dll
- dnnl.dll
- nvinfer.dll
- nvinfer_plugin.dll
- onnxruntime.dll

